03963nam a22006015i 9780822375104DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20152015ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015015087  a97808223751047 a10.1515/97808223751042doi  a(DE-B1597)552840  a(OCoLC)915113144  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aPS153.N5bE39 2015 4aPS153.N5bE39 2015 7aSOC0010002bisacsh04a810.9/8960732231 aEllis, Nadia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTerritories of the Soul :bQueered Belonging in the Black Diaspora /cNadia Ellis. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b5 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Queer Elsewhere of Black Diaspora -- tOne. The Attachments of C. L. R. James -- tTwo. The Fraternal Agonies of Baldwin and Lamming -- tThree. Andrew Salkey and the Queer Diasporic -- tFour. Burning Spear and Nathaniel Mackey at Large -- tEpilogue: Dancehall's Urban Possessions -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNadia Ellis attends to African diasporic belonging as it comes into being through black expressive culture. Living in the diaspora, Ellis asserts, means existing between claims to land and imaginative flights unmoored from the earth-that is, to live within the territories of the soul. Drawing on the work of Jose Muñoz, Ellis connects queerness' utopian potential with diasporic aesthetics. Occupying the territory of the soul, being neither here nor there, creates in diasporic subjects feelings of loss, desire, and a sensation of a pull from elsewhere. Ellis locates these phenomena in the works of C.L.R. James, the testy encounter between George Lamming and James Baldwin at the 1956 Congress of Negro Artists and Writers in Paris, the elusiveness of the queer diasporic subject in Andrew Salkey's novel Escape to an Autumn Pavement, and the trope of spirit possession in Nathaniel Mackey's writing and Burning Spear's reggae. Ellis' use of queer and affect theory shows how geographies claim diasporic subjects in ways that nationalist or masculinist tropes can never fully capture. Diaspora, Ellis concludes, is best understood as a mode of feeling and belonging, one fundamentally shaped by the experience of loss.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aAfrican diaspora. 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCaribbean literaturexBlack authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aGroup identity. 0aQueer theory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822375104zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822375104423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822375104.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles